observations.recommendation:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of Inventories and submit the required RPCI and RPCSP to the Audit Team within the prescribed deadline in strict adherence with Section 124, Chapter 7, of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to prepare the required supporting registry, forms and other reports pursuant to COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to henceforth record the purchased relief goods as debit to Welfare Goods for Distribution account instead of the used Donations account in line with the perpetual inventory method and in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015, to come up with a reliable and accurate financial information.

Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System of the local government unit;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the Report on Local Road Network, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with a complete description and cost segregation of road components for all road projects; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the prescribed Local Road Network Ledger Card and ensure the timely recording of completed road projects and recompute the depreciation for Calendar Year 2024 to reflect the accurate asset valuation and reliable financial reporting.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to secure the necessary documents to facilitate the payment and release of the retention monies amounting to ₱1,523,319.74 pursuant to pertinent provisions of Section 62 of the 2016 RIRR of R.A. No. 9184. Any amount due to the LGU by the concerned suppliers/contractors shall be deducted therefrom;
Consider reverting to the Government Equity the amount of ₱577,064.20 which remained unclaimed for more than two (2) years, if warranted, in line with Section 98 of P.D. No. 1445; and
Revisit Section 54.5 of the 2016 RIRR of R.A. No. 9184 and adopt a policy clearly defining the mode of procurement and the nature of project when retention monies shall only be required.

Immediately submit the complete copies of the Original Certificate of Ownership and all Certificate Intermediate Transfer to attest the ownership of the LGU, otherwise the transaction may be suspended in audit;
Thereafter, instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue Certificates of Ownership and Certificates of Transfer to the tobacco farmers/beneficiaries as legal proof of their ownership; and
Formulate its own policy and guidelines in selecting bona fide beneficiaries/ tobacco farmers to ensure fairness and transparency in the selection process.

Direct the Petty Cash Custodian (PCC) to prepare Petty Cash Vouchers (PCVs) to document the payments or disbursements from the Petty Cash;
Refrain from paying financial assistance/AICS from the Petty Cash, and henceforth ensure that the fund shall only be used to non-regular, non-recurring, emergency and petty operating expenses of the LGU in compliance with COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Section 48 of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual for LGUs, Volume I; and
Designate a Special Disbursing Officer to handle the payment of AICS through Cash Advance which will allow greater accountability, transparency and to properly monitor the use of fund through liquidation.

Come up with written policy guidelines relative to the hiring and re-hiring of JO and COS workers in the executive to establish a clear expectation and protect the rights of both the workers and the Municipality;
Provide Statement of Duties and Responsibilities of JO and COS workers to clearly identify their responsibilities and to guide them to perform their duties efficiently and effectively; and
Set a standardized rate based on their qualifications and suitability for the job applied, and periodically review the competitiveness and reasonableness of the said rates subject to the Municipality’s financial capacity.

We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
a. 	Inventory Committee to formulate plans to complete the physical count of the Municipality’s PPE and prepare the RPCPPE under COA Circular No. 2020-006;
b.	Local Treasurer to prepare and maintain Property Cards and to reconcile balances thereof with that of the accounting records regularly pursuant to Sections 119 and 120 of NGAS Manual for LGUs;
c. Disposal and Appraisal Committee to fast track the immediate disposal of unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration and consequent reduction in their value; and
d. Municipal Accountant to account for the disposed properties and make journal entries to properly book the asset account in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Make the necessary adjusting entries for transactions that have already been completed and liquidated;
Reconcile dormant and long-outstanding balances with the identified source agencies to determine the status of funds;
Return the unutilized funds to the concerned NGAs or, if deemed appropriate, request the necessary authority to use the funds; and
Implement a system to monitor the status of funds, ensure prompt implementation of the PPAs, and timely submit the liquidation reports and refund the unutilized funds.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to terminate the above-mentioned time deposits;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to exhaust all means to verify the details regarding the initial opening of the HYSA/Time Deposit Accounts and identify the specific sources of the funds used for these investments;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct errors; and
Ensure that subsequent placement of time deposits complies with the applicable laws, rules, and regulations.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Make the necessary adjusting entries to the Repairs and Maintenance-Buildings and Other Structures account;
Recognize the cost of replacing part of an item of PPE in the carrying amount of the item, and derecognize the carrying amount of the part that has been replaced;
Ensure that appropriate journal entries are made to recognize corresponding depreciation and accumulated depreciation and to adjust the Government Equity account; and
Ensure the proper recording of the transactions under the Repairs and Maintenance-Building and Other Structures Account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Determine and adjust the unreconciled reciprocal transactions for CY 2022 amounting to a net amount of ₱83,462.77 supported by duly prepared CY 2022 General Ledgers and Journal Entry Vouchers for its corresponding adjustments;

Determine whether the previous Municipal Accountant recognized the unrecorded receivable/payable accounts pertaining to the CY 2021 and CY 2020 misstatements with the following journal entries:

If the same was not yet adjusted, recognize the aforementioned adjustments to correct the unreconciled intra-agency transactions; 

Trace the discrepancies between the balances of the accounts Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds amounting to ₱5,561,271.48 and effect the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts through the preparation of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) duly supported with documents, explanations and/or computations in order to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements.  Henceforth, see to it that reciprocal accounts have the same balances all the time.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the following:

Municipal Treasurer to:

i.	Strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the municipality;

ii.	Conduct verification on transactions recorded by the municipality and compare it to the amount of sales declared on renewal of business permits. Likewise, regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments should be conducted to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;

iii.	Enforce collection of the underdeclared sales noted with corresponding interest, surcharges, and penalties;


iv.	Require business establishments to submit their Income Tax Return filed on or before April 30 and enforce collection for deficiency of business taxes noted; 

v.	 Set up or institutionalize a standard computation that could arrive in a more realistic basis of business taxes in the absence of the required audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration of the gross receipts;

vi.	Collect the business taxes and penalties to four contractors in the aggregate amount of at least ₱268,301.78; and thereafter


vii. Impose business tax to contractors engaging business with the municipality in conformity with the Municipal Revenue Code.

b.	Municipal Business and Permits Licensing Officer (MBPLO) to:

i.	Refrain from accepting application for the renewal of business permits that are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns, particularly when the taxpayer submit the prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;

ii.	Require submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes; and

iii.	Maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their tax payment for ease of monitoring.

We recommended that: The Local Chief Executive and Local Sanggunian shall formulate clear-cut guidelines on allocations for mobile communications and data services and consider the cheaper, prevailing rates offered by mobile networks;
Management shall grant the communication allowance to officials and employees wherein communication is of utmost importance; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure completeness of supporting documents and make certain that used cards are surrendered by prepaid card users prior to processing and payment of communication allowance to guarantee prudent use of government resources.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
OIC-GSO and concerned Offices to (i) prepare and furnish the MAO on a monthly basis the copies of SSMI supported with RIS and/or proof of distribution of goods and supplies; and


(ii) reconcile the RPCI with Inventory accounts in GL; and

Municipal Accountant to (i) conduct a thorough review of the Inventory accounts and tally with the Offices concerned; 

(ii) derecognize in the books the items which were already consumed and/or distributed to end-users in a timely manner;

(iii) and record all procurement of inventory supplies in the books using the Perpetual Inventory System.

3.7	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
a.	Inventory committee to expedite the conduct of inventory taking and render a report thereon in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
b.	Municipal Accountant and Property Officer to reconcile their records and furnish the inventory committee a copy thereto to assist the committee in the conduct of the physical count of the PPE;
Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary correction/adjustment in the PPE account based on the inventory report; and
Municipal GSO to account the missing properties and follow the procedures in the relief from property accountability under COA Memorandum 92-751.

We recommended that Management:
require the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Council (LDRRMC) to review the existing PPAs under the LDRRMF to determine the relevance and responsiveness of the projects to the present circumstances including the reasonableness of project costing and make the necessary revisions as warranted subject to the appropriate approvals;
direct the LDRRMO to strictly monitor the implementation of the PPAs to facilitate the timely completion thereof;
essure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC. Accordingly, intensive procurement planning and coordination with stakeholders shall be conducted prior to the inclusion of PPAs in the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;
instruct the LDRRM Officer to include in its LDRRMFIP for the current year, in a separate section, the list of projects and activities to be funded from the unexpended LDRRMF in previous years of the Special Trust Fund; and
direct the parties involved in the preparation of the LDRRM budget to observe the documentary requirements and procedures prescribed in COA Circular No.  2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 for the implementation of programs, projects and activities.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to secure the available documents and information pertaining to the Due from Local Government Units account balance and determine whether these are sufficient to assert validity of claim of LGU Cabatuan, Isabela. Thereupon, issue Demand Letters to the concerned local government units and exhaust all possible remedies to collect the receivables;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to verify, analyze, and validate the existence of the receivables and if appropriate, secure the necessary documents to support the request for write-off of the dormant receivables amounting to ₱1.202 million and follow the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts prescribed by COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary Adjusting Journal Entries (AJE) to correct the balance of Due from Local Government Units account and record the procurement and distribution of the Construction Materials for Distribution amounting to ₱9.322 million in the respective books of the municipality and the barangays; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to recognize Allowance for Impairment on the remaining Due from Local Government Units balance of ₱1.353 million pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 to come up with a more accurate and reliable financial information.

Issue demand letters to the concerned individuals and exhaust all possible remedies to collect the Accounts Receivable balance of ₱2.461 million;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to secure the necessary documents to support the request for write-off of the dormant receivables amounting to ₱0.504 million, if deemed appropriate, and follow the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts provided by COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to recognize allowance for impairment on the Accounts Receivable balance pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 to come up with a more accurate and reliable financial information.

Immediately conduct reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts and prepare the necessary adjustments to come up with a more reliable and accurate financial information in line with Section 21 of IPSAS and Section 111 of P.D. 1445;
If appropriate, secure the necessary documents to support the request for write-off of the dormant and unreconciled balance of Due from Other Funds and follow the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts prescribed by COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023; and
Henceforth ensure that intra-agency transactions are immediately settled and monitored to avoid accumulation of unreconciled balances.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and update its Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card based on the database and assessment roll of the Municipal Assessor and thereafter forward a copy of certified list of the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year to the Municipal Accountant as the basis in setting-up the Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivable;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to set-up the Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivable at the beginning of the year which shall exclude the advance payments already collected during the previous year; and
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the master list of RPT delinquencies to the Municipal Accountant and require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to evaluate and analyze the discrepancies between the tax delinquencies of RPT reported in the financial statements as of the year ending December 31, 2023 and the list of tax delinquencies extracted from the electronic Government Application System (e-GAPS). Thereafter, effect the necessary adjustments to come up with a more accurate and reliable financial information in view of Section 27 of International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS 1) and Section 111 of P.D. 1445.

Ensure that the appropriated amounts of the 20% Development Fund are fully utilized in the implementation of the lined-up projects contained in the approved Annual Investment Plan (AIP);
Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Council (MPDC) to include in the Annual Investment Plan (AIP) only those projects that can be implemented during the year through efficient planning and procurement activities in line with Section 3.2.3 of DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 1 dated November 4, 2020;
Direct the Municipal Engineer, in cooperation with the concerned heads of Implementing Departments, to closely monitor the utilization and implementation of priority projects which are essential to the promotion of general welfare of the people and to maximize the usage of the 20% development fund as mandated under DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1; and
If necessary, consider requesting for the reprogramming of the savings from the completed projects totaling to ₱1.369 million to other development projects which will be contained in the revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) to facilitate its appropriate release and utilization.

The Municipal Mayor, together with the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (MDRRMC), prudently plan the utilization of the LDRRM Fund focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management;
The MDRRMO include in the subsequent Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) only those that can be implemented during the year through efficient planning and procurement activities;
If necessary, consider requesting for the reprogramming of the savings from the completed projects totaling to P220,815.47 and the reappropriation of unexpended balance of QRF and DRRM-MOOE for CYs 2019-2022 amounting to ₱3,022,416.12 to other eligible disaster mitigating projects by including the said balances in a separate caption in the subsequent LDRRMFIP and in the revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) to facilitate its appropriate release and utilization; and
The MDRRMO, together with the Municipal Engineer and in cooperation with the heads of other offices concerned, expedite and ensure the full implementation of all identified priority PPAs to optimize the utilization of the LDRRM Fund.

Direct the concerned heads of offices to analyze the validity of all its recorded liabilities in the Trust Fund and its available cash and cash equivalents to measure the liquidity of the LGU and determine its ability to pay off its debt;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the Trust Fund is exclusively used for the purpose/s for which they were granted pursuant to Section 4(3) of P.D. No. 1445 and Sections 305(e) and 309(b) of R.A. No. 7160; and
Ensure the full implementation of PPAs and the immediate liquidation of the transferred funds to the source agencies.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:
(a) coordination of the City Treasurer, CBLIPO, and Sangguniang Panlungsod to (i) regularly   review and update the City Revenue Code at least every five years, as mandated by law, in order to optimize its revenue generation for the benefit of its constituents; (ii) ensure that the amended Revenue Code reflects the current economic conditions and complies with the Local Government Code of 1991;
(b)  City Treasurer to (i) use available records in her office in validating the declared sales of taxpayers in securing business permit with the City; and (ii) secure from the OCA any reports that can be useful in the assessment of business tax for business entities that have transaction with the City;
(c)   CBLIPO to  be more strict in the implementation and enforcement of the City Revenue Code; and
(d) City Treasurer  and CBLIPO to verify, assess, and validate other businesses aside from the noted business taxpayers and demand the payment of computed under collection of business taxes amounting to ₱75,232.53.

We recommended that:
10.15.1 	The City Accounting and the General Services Offices, in coordination with the members of the Inventory Committee, continuously fast-track the reconciliation of the PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 and ensure the immediate and regular reconciliation of records of both offices pertaining to the City’s PPEs;
10.15.2 	The City Accounting Office maintain the required Property Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) or its equivalent to record all acquisitions, depreciations, disposals and other information about the PPE in compliance with COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002, and to facilitate the reconciliation of any noted discrepancy between the records of the Accounting and the General Services Offices;
10.15.3	The City Accountant provide disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements for CY 2023 the required details/information for the Property, Plant and Equipment including Total Road Network System in accordance with IPSAS provisions and COA Circular No. 2016-004 dated               September 30, 2016.
10.15.4	The City facilitate the application of a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
10.15.5	The City consider increasing the number of personnel in the Accounting Office to address the manpower constraints in the said Office and facilitate the maintenance of the required records.

observations.managementAction:
The PRAISE Committee and Local Finance Committee (LFC) discontinued the practice of granting across-the-board payment of other PRAISE Incentives to its employees;

The PRAISE Committee and LFC established suitable criteria in the selection of deserving employees who will receive the PRAISE granted.


The PRAISE Committee and LFC submitted justification on how the awards received by employees resulted in monetary savings and why other PRAISE incentives exceeded the allowable cap.

observations.recommendation:
The City mobilize an Inspectorate Committee with adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less, who will coordinate with the City General Services Office (CGSO) in the preparation of a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to promote the conduct of the required annual physical count of PPE and preparation of the pertinent report, in compliance with COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and to address the unreconciled balances between the Accounting Office and CGSO caused by non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability;

The City Accounting Office maintain the required Property Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) or its equivalent to record all acquisitions, depreciations, disposals and other information about the PPE to facilitate the reconciliation of any noted discrepancy between the records of the Accounting and the General Services Offices;

The City facilitate the application of a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

The City consider increasing the number of personnel in the Accounting Office to address the manpower constraints in the said Office and facilitate the maintenance of the required records.

The City make representations with the System and Plan Integrator and Development Corporation (SPIDC) to take the necessary actions to resolve the noted unreconciled balances between the Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms (RAAF) module and the Form Control Receipt module in the Treasury Operations and Income Monitoring System (TOIMS) to facilitate report generation when needed;

The City Treasurer maintain a logbook for the manual recording of the receipts/purchases and the issuances of the accountable forms to ensure proper monitoring of the inventory of accountable forms; and

The City Treasurer, in compliance with Sections 50 and 51 of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual for Local Government Units (LGUs), Volume II:

Ensure monthly submissions by each of the Accountable Officers of the required Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms (RAAF);

Prepare the Consolidated Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms and submit the same to the Auditor concerned not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month; and

Hasten the reconciliation and the preparation of RAAF as of the cash examination cut-off date which is on             November 17, 2022 and the immediate submission of the same to the Auditor.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant in coordination of Municipal Treasurer to:
exert effort to collect these long outstanding receivables particularly the accounts with available reference documents by sending demand letters. Exhaust all remedies to collect and properly document efforts made;
exert more effort to locate all related documents pertaining to the long outstanding receivables in order to establish their existence and validity;
For the receivables that are proven to be uncollectible but duly supported with required documents, we recommended that the LCE request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.
We further recommended that LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to recognize allowance for impairment of receivables in accordance with IPSAS to present fairly the financial statements.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Bids and Awards Committee to:
Require the implementing units of all infrastructure projects of the Municipality to prepare a PPMP that shall be incorporated in the APP;
Prepare the APP using the prescribed format of the GPPB;
Make sure that the entirety of the procurement activities that will be undertaken by the Municipality within the calendar year are reflected in the APP; and
Capacitate and keep themselves abreast concerning updates on procurement law and preparation of APP and apply it in the discharge of their functions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Engineer/Building to Official to:
provide status on those issued building permits without occupancy permits and impose necessary fees for completed projects, and thereafter, monitor those issued with building permits to secure occupancy permits first before actually occupying the structures constructed;
submit a listing or copy of building permits and occupancy permits issued per month to the Municipal Assessor in order to be used as basis for assessment and updating of the Assessment Roll;
Tap the Barangay Officials to report to the Building Official monthly/quarterly, whichever is more suitable, the on-going construction and completed structures in their barangays in order to facilitate the Building Official in monitoring compliance of the structures with the National Building Code of the Philippines and maximize income generated therewith;
Direct the Municipal Assessor to verify and assess the real properties that have been previously issued with building permits and occupancy permit and ensure that they are immediately included in the RPT assessment roll, as applicable.

We recommended Management the following:
The Municipal Accountant must (1) recognize in the LGU books the depreciation of the above-mentioned PPE accounts to correctly report their balances at year-end and (2) make the corresponding adjusting entries on the identified misclassified accounts;
Effect the mark “FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY” observing the required size of three (3) inches and the corresponding name of the LGU on each side of the vehicle to prevent unnecessary and unofficial use of government vehicles;
Instruct responsible official to process the timely registration of serviceable properties to avoid penalties;
Ensure that all properties of the LGU are registered in the name of the Municipality of Cabatuan;
Strictly comply with the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and
Fairly present in the financial statements the substance of transactions, not merely their form, to achieve a more faithfully represented PPE account in compliance to IPSAS 1.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries relative to the misclassified/misstated accounts;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their reports to establish the correct balances and the former must immediately transfer the cash back-up of the special trust fund (QRF & MOOE-Mitigation Fund) to the trust fund books;
Strictly and prudently comply with all the rules and regulations laid out relative to LDRRM Fund.

We recommended Management to:
Direct the concerned officials to reconcile the above-noted discrepancies in the Annual Budget and in the other submitted documents;
Instruct the concerned officials to prepare the Plan and Budget with sufficient details and information and that all changes in the Budget were duly supported by ordinances and other documents;
Submit justification on the reasonableness of the cash allowance for meals granted to several personnel;
Ensure that all relevant documentary requirements involving LDRRM Fund transactions are duly provided to establish their propriety, legality and validity;
Allocate PPAs that are in line with the specific projects and activities to support disaster risk management activities; and
Enjoin all concerned officials to strictly comply with the above-stated law, rules and regulations.

We recommended that Management:

o provide a written explanation on the non-deduction of 1% retention as   warranty of these procured goods and strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 to deduct 1% retention from the payments of goods to the suppliers, and ensure that conditions set forth by the law are observed;

o submit full accounting of these goods, duly received by the recipients including their complete addresses duly noted and supervised by the MSWDO; 

o submit list of patients/beneficiaries of the test kits with their complete addresses including other related information as basis in undergoing test, duly noted by the Municipal Health Officer; and

o ensure completeness of documentation before effecting payment on all transactions, to comply with the requirements of pertinent rules and regulations.

We recommended and the Local Executive Officer agreed to direct:
The Municipal Accountant to adjust the Cash in Bank, LCCA and other affected accounts pertaining to the misstatements amounting to ₱1,577,015.96;
The Municipal Accountant to utilize the “We Access” of the depository bank or request copies of snapshot so that she could timely and regularly prepare Bank Reconciliation Statements in order to maximize its benefits as a monitoring and detective control;
The Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of including the interest income in the Report of Collection and Deposit; and
The Municipal Treasurer to inform the payees to surrender the previously issued checks and issue new checks upon surrender of the stale checks by the payee.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
Municipal Accountant to
Recognize Welfare Goods Expense and Transfer from General Fund of Unspent DRRMF amounting to ₱1,693,594.00 in order to correct the misstatement;
Record all purchases of supplies and materials regardless of whether or not they are consumed within the accounting period as inventory following the perpetual inventory method; and
Prepare JEV to record expenditures only when SSMI is submitted by the GSO-Designate;
The GSO-Designate to ubmit copies of Requisition and Issue Slip and Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued for the distributed welfare goods, drugs and medicines, and medical supplies.

We recommended the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Submit the lacking supporting documents in order to avoid suspension of the transactions;


Procure ordinary and regular office supplies based on the consolidated APP to avoid piecemeal procurement

We recommended the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Submit the lacking supporting documents in order to avoid suspension of the transactions;


Procure ordinary and regular office supplies based on the consolidated APP to avoid piecemeal procurement

We reiterated our recommendation and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of all Property, Plant and Equipment and consequently prepare and submit a Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) not later than January 31 of each year;
Property Officer Designate to:
maintain property cards per category of PPE;
ensure that all equipment procured and issued to end-users have property tags of the Municipality for easy identification; and
keep and maintain copies of all Acknowledgment Receipt for Equipment (ARE);
OIC Municipal Accountant to:
maintain  Subsidiary Ledger Cards for all PPEs;
exert effort in reconciling her records with the Property Officer Designate.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
Municipal Engineer to complete the cost segregation and mapping of Local Road Network and furnish copy of report to the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer Designate;
Property Officer Designate to render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map using the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015; and
Inventory Committee to prepare and submit Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive direct the Accounting unit to disclose in the notes to financial the necessary information that may be relevant for decision-making of stakeholders.

We recommended and the Local Executive Officer agreed to direct the:
Municipal Treasurer to timely submit all documents to the OIC-Municipal Accountant in order to avoid delay in recording all transactions and to cancel the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the accountant with the duplicate copies of Disbursement Voucher (DV) and its supporting documents, for the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher following the procedures prescribed to ensure recording of cancellation;
Municipal Treasurer to call the attention or inform the payees of those cancelled checks to surrender the stale checks to her so she could issue new checks;
OIC-Municipal Accountant to exert efforts to obtain necessary documents to support the identified reconciling items to effect the needed adjustments; and henceforth, ensure that all identified reconciling items are analyzed, fully documented and recorded in the books.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct:
The City Accountant-
in coordination with the CSWDO, effect the reconciliation of account balance with that Office and accordingly enter the necessary adjustment/correction, if any, in the accounting reports and records.
issue follow-up demand letters to the persons accountable/liable for the recovery of the outstanding receivables;
exhaust all possible remedies/actions for the recovery of the subject receivables and, if warranted, file appropriate request for a possible write-off of dormant accounts; and
The City Social Welfare Development Officer (SWDO) to-
revisit the Memorandum of Agreement governing the implementation of SEA program and ensure that the provisions stipulated therein are strictly observed in order to protect the interest of the government;
issue follow-up/series of  demand letters to the delinquent borrowers requiring them to pay in accordance with the scheduled amortization to recover the overdue receivables;
conduct monitoring and post–evaluation on the status and result of the project; and
in coordination with the Accounting Office, effect the reconciliation of account balance with that Office and accordingly enter the necessary adjustment/correction in the corresponding reports and records.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct-
The Offices/Unit Heads concerned to:
provide competent documents, such as detailed work plan  for the particular Saturdays and the corresponding validated accomplishment report  that would corroborate on the management’s assertion that the individuals under the JO contracts actually reported for work during additional workdays (Saturdays) as reflected in the Daily Time Records (DTRs);
keep, maintain records of the job order individuals assigned in their respective units, such as the daily attendance log book and record of daily accomplishments. Utilize the same as reference in checking the correctness of the Daily Time Records (DTRs) and accomplishments being submitted by the subject workers;
The City Accountant to (a) ensure that review on the completeness of supporting documents on claims for the payment of wages are thoroughly reviewed, particularly for additional work days of individuals under the job order contracts; and
The City Human Resource Management Officer to submit explanation and/ or justification on the inclusion of Saturdays and Holidays as additional regular workdays for the selected individuals whose work designation are administrative and office work in nature. Further, timely provide the Office of the Auditor with copy of approved job order contracts to facilitate timely review and evaluation.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive directed the-
City Treasurer to adopt more efficient procedures to ensure that all payment will be immediately release to the respective claimants in order to facilitate the prompt transmittal of transaction documents, such as cash/check disbursement vouchers, etc. together with complete supporting documents, to the Accounting Office for recording and timely submission to the Office of the COA Auditor for post-audit and evaluation;
City Accountant to ensure completeness of supporting documents before certifying the claim and allowing its payment. Further, strictly adhere with the provision of COA Circular No. 2009-006 on submission of reports, accounts and transaction documents for post-audit to timely determine the regularity and validity of the transaction and correctness of the reported account balances.

We recommended and management agreed that the (i) CGSO  strictly comply with the required maintenance of complete and updated PPELCs and PCs, respectively for each class of property and to record the acquisition, adjustments and disposal thereof; 

(ii) Inventory Committee exert extra effort to complete the physical inventory of all property, plant, and equipment of the City Government and reconcile the report with the accounting records; and 




(iii) observe the consistent submission of the physical inventory reports on PPEs to the Office of the Auditor for review and validation not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to existing rules and regulations; 




Moreover, the City Accountant, City Assessor and Heads of the General Services Office (GSO) and City Planning and Development Office (CPDO) (i) coordinate with each other and reconcile their records to ascertain the correctness of the Land account balance; and 




(ii) facilitate the registration in the name of City Government the parcel of lots acquired which were not yet covered by TCT to preclude third party claims over said properties; 

Finally, we recommended that the Accounting Office recognize in the books of accounts all unrecorded parcels of land acquired by the City and maintain Real Property Ledger Card for each and every parcel of land/PPEs owned by the City.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Head of the General Services Office to (a) cause the preparation of the updated Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property together with the corresponding assessment, evaluation and appraisal reports; 



(b) facilitate the submission of request for disposal of said PPEs to the Office of the Auditor for inspection, evaluation and review by the COA Technical Services Office; 




(c) ensure that after receipt of favorable COA recommendation on the request,  undertake immediate disposal of the subject properties to prevent further deterioration, decline of value and in order to generate additional funds from sale thereof; and 




(d) prepare and submit  schedule of disposal of assets once the same became unserviceable and beyond economical repairs to avoid the accumulation of unserviceable PPEs in the storage facility and to prevent the recurrence of similar lapses.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the (a) Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to thoroughly double check the completeness of the required documents submitted by the bidders; 

(b) Office of the City Accountant to be more diligent in ensuring the completeness of the required supporting documents prior to its indorsement to the Office of the LCE for final approval; 

(c) City Engineering Office conduct constant site inspection and strict monitoring on the status of implementation to prevent unnecessary delay in the completion of projects; and 


(d) the City Engineer and the 
City Accountant to observe the imposition of liquidated damages for unjustified delay in completion of project, if warranted, to protect the interest of the City Government and to compel the contractor to complete the projects at the earliest possible time.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the (a) Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) ensure the correctness of the contents of Notices prior to posting at PhilGEPS website; and 


(ii) thoroughly double check the completeness and accuracy of the technical and financial proposals submitted by the bidders; 

(b) City Engineering Office to (i) be more diligent in the preparation of documents by ensuring all necessary data and bases of computation of ABC are considered in order to arrive at the amount most advantageous to the government; 

(ii) specify in the Bill of Quantities (BOQ) the  items of works to be performed and the respective quantities of materials needed per scope of work; 

(iii) make detailed estimates of every costs in the Program of Works (POW); and 

(iv) conduct constant site inspection and strict monitoring on the status of implementation to prevent unnecessary delay in the completion of projects; and 




(iii) the City Engineer and the City Accountant to observe the imposition of corresponding liquidated damages, if warranted, to protect the interest of the City Government and to compel the contractor to complete the projects within the contract period.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (a) instruct the BAC Chairperson to submit written explanation on the occurrence of repeated errors and/or misrepresentation in the publication of Invitation to Bid (ITBs); 

(b) adopt internal control systems/measures that will ensure the correctness of the invitation to bid posted by the BAC to prevent the incurrence of similar lapses; 

(c) if possible, assign additional support staff in the BAC Secretariat unit that will help facilitate timely review of entries prior to posting at the website; 

(d) conduct verification/investigation to determine the real reasons and the persons primarily accountable behind the noted errors in publication, if needed; and 

(e) consider the upgrading of internet services to cope up with the  need in facilitating the required publication of procurement activities of the agency, if necessary.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the Chairman and Members of the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to observe prudence in the performance of their respective duties and functions,  particularly in (a) determining the reasonable prices to be used in setting up of Budget for the Contract which should be the most advantageous to the government; 

(b) conducting evaluation by considering all factors, such as the specification, brand, prices and others that may contribute in rendering decision favorable to the agency; and 

(c) preventing the recurrence of similar lapses to avoid wastage of government resources.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (i) direct the City Planning and Development Officer to monitor the effective and efficient implementation of the projects under the 20% Development Fund so that necessary interventions by the implementing offices may be made for their timely completion; 

(ii) ensure that development projects for inclusion in the 20% Development Fund have been thoroughly studied and prioritized; and 




(iii) continue to invest in high–impact or developmental projects for inclusion in the Annual Investment Plan.

We recommended and management agreed to (a) direct the CSWDO and the City Accountant to (i) strictly adhere to the fundamental principles in the disbursement of funds prescribed under Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445;

(ii) observe full compliance with the requirements consistent with the guidelines of the DSWD in the implementation of Cash for Work for Climate Change  Adaption and Mitigation Program; 

(iii) facilitate the immediate submission of validated daily accomplishment reports together with the certified pictures taken during the actual implementation of the program; and 

(b) direct the Disbursing Officer concerned to explain in writing the deficiencies noted on the questionable signatures of claimants appearing in the daily time records and IDs.

We likewise recommended that payments to cash for work laborers, and other workers like job orders, casuals, etc. should be made by the designated Disbursing Officer after the presentation of Identification Card to ensure fulfillment of obligation to right persons and prevent fictitious transactions.

In view of the foregoing lapses, we recommended and management agreed that the City Mayor:

require the officials of the Farmers’ Association/Cooperatives to initiate coordination with the owners of the lots where the MPDP were constructed to discuss the possible donation/transfer of the parcel of land used in the project in favor of the government;

ensure that the requirement on ownership of land, by the City Government, where the project will be constructed must first be met before its implementation in order to avoid occurrence of similar deficiency;

instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and BAC Secretariat to strictly observe the required posting of Notices in the PhilGEPS website within the period as prescribed under Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of IRR of RA No. 9184; and

remind the City Accountant to (i) cause the immediate submission of the required supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor for review and evaluation; and 

(ii) strictly adhere to the fundamental principles in the disbursement of funds prescribed under Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 on the submission of complete documentation for every claim against government funds to avoid the recurrence of similar lapses.

